#MEM id=cohort-analysis source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/kai/skills/custom/cohort-analysis/SKILL.md savings=4%
M||tx|---
M||name|cohort-al
M||desc|ka's cohort retention al framework for hb (SaaS) and nz (e-commerce). Covers cohort table structure, churn calculation, trial-to-paid funnel, LTV projection from cohort data, and sb query templates.
M||vers|1.0.0
M||tx|---
M|Purp|tx|hb's North Star is MRR + trial-to-paid conversion. Flat averages hide cohort-level decay. A 10% average churn rate can mask a 30% churn rate in the first 30 days w/ 2% thereafter — those two businesses have completely different interventions. This skill ensures ka never reports a flat average when cohort data is available.
M|Purp|tx|---
M|When|it|Any al of hb retention, churn, or LTV
M|When|it|Monthly hb health rv
M|When|it|When fx md runway and needs cohort-based LTV inputs
M|When|it|When nt designs a churn-prevention experiment and needs baseline cohort data
M|When|tx|---
M|Coho|tx|Group us by the week they converted from trial to paid.
M|Coho|tx|```sql
M|Coho|-- S|trial-to-paid cohorts (replace table names w/ actual sc)
M|Coho|tx|SELECT
M|Coho|tx|DATE_TRUNC('week', trial_started_at) AS cohort_week,
M|Coho|tx|COUNT(*) AS trial_starts,
M|Coho|tx|COUNT(CASE WHEN converted_at IS NOT NULL THEN 1 END) AS conversions,
M|Coho|tx|ROUND(100.0 * COUNT(CASE WHEN converted_at IS NOT NULL THEN 1 END) / COUNT(*), 1) AS conversion_rate_pct
M|Coho|tx|FROM hourbour_users
M|Coho|tx|GROUP BY cohort_week
M|Coho|tx|ORDER BY cohort_week DESC
M|Coho|tx|LIMIT 12;
M|Coho|tx|```
M|Rete|tx|For each cohort, measure what % of paying us remain active at M1, M2, M3, M6.
M|Rete|tx|```
M|Rete|tx|Cohort Week \| M0 (100%) \| M1 \| M2 \| M3 \| M6
M|Rete|tx|2026-W20    \| 100       \| 72 \| 61 \| 55 \| 48
M|Rete|tx|2026-W19    \| 100       \| 68 \| 57 \| 51 \| —
M|Rete|tx|```
M|Rete|**Re|** If M1 retention drops below 65%, the onboarding is broken — not the pd. rt to nt.
M|Rete|**Re|** If M1 is strong but M3 drops sharply, the pd has a value cliff — rt to mc.
M|Rete|tx|---
M|LTV |tx|Do not use flat churn rate for LTV. Use the cohort retention curve.
M|LTV |tx|```
M|LTV |tx|LTV = ARPU × Σ(retention_rate_at_month_n) for n = 1 to 24
M|LTV |tx|= ARPU × (M1 + M2 + M3 + ... + M24)
M|LTV |tx|```
M|LTV |tx|If only 6 months of data exist, project M7–M24 using the M3→M6 decay slope.
M|LTV |tx|Flag the projection as estimated beyond the data window.
M|LTV |**Al|**
M|LTV |tx|```
M|LTV |LTV |$[lo] – $[hi]
M|LTV |Base|[n] months of cohort data (M1–M6)
M|LTV |Proj|linear decay from M3→M6 slope
M|LTV |Conf|[lo \| MED \| hi] depending on cohort sample size
M|LTV |tx|```
M|LTV |tx|---
M|Novi|For |
M|Novi|tx|```
M|Novi|tx|Cohort Month \| Orders \| Repeat 60d \| Repeat 90d \| AOV avg
M|Novi|tx|2026-04      \| 142    \| 18%        \| 24%        \| £84
M|Novi|tx|2026-03      \| 98     \| 22%        \| 31%        \| £91
M|Novi|tx|```
M|Novi|**Ke|**
M|Novi|- **|** below 15% = weak retention
M|Novi|- **|** if AOV drops over time for a cohort, pd-mk fit is weakening
M|Novi|- **|** which acquisition month generates the most lifetime rv?
M|Novi|tx|---
M|Outp|Ever|
M|Outp|tx|```
M|Outp|tx|COHORT rp — [vt] — [date]
M|Outp|1. D|[earliest cohort] to [latest cohort] — [n] months
M|Outp|2. C|Trial-to-paid [X%] — [vs prior 4-week avg: +/-X%]
M|Outp|3. M|[X%] — [RED/AMBER/GREEN vs 65% threshold]
M|Outp|4. L|$[lo]–$[hi] — [confidence level]
M|Outp|5. K|[one in — what the cohort data says that a flat average hides]
M|Outp|6. R|[who needs to act on this: nt (onboarding) / mc (st) / fx (md up)]
M|Outp|tx|```
M|Outp|tx|---
M|Anti|it|Never rp a single churn rate w/o breaking it by cohort week
M|Anti|it|Never extrapolate beyond 2× the data window (6 months of data → max 12-month projection)
M|Anti|it|Never rp hb cohort data to the nz sn context (vt isolation rule)
M|Anti|it|Never give fx a point estimate for LTV — always a range w/ confidence level